<HEADLINE>
FT  07 APR 94 / Assassination claim as African presidents die
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LESLIE CRAWFORD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NAIROBI
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The presidents of Rwanda and Burundi were killed yesterday when their
aircraft crashed while landing at Kigali, the Rwandan capital. The aircraft
was hit by rocket fire in a double assassination, according to Rwandan
diplomats.
Rwandan President Major-General Juvenal Habyarimana and Burundi President
Cyprien Ntaryamira were flying back from a regional meeting in Dar Es Salaam
on ways to end conflict between Hutu and Tutsi ethnic groups in both
countries. Their deaths are a blow to peace moves.
In Burundi more than 100,000 people are believed to have died since the
killing last October of the country's first democratically elected
president.
Mr Ntaryamira, from the majority Hutu tribe, was recently nominated by a
cabinet of both Hutus and Tutsis, although he had been unable to halt
sporadic clashes. More than 400,000 Burundi refugees remain in squalid camps
in neighbouring countries.
Although the cause of the air crash was not officially confirmed, diplomats
believe Gen Habyarimana had amassed enough political enemies during his 20
years in power in Rwanda to give credence to assassination claims. Gen
Habyarimana, a Hutu, signed a ceasefire with the rebel Rwandese Patriotic
Front in 1992 but there have been delays in implementing peace. In spite of
the presence of 2,500 UN peacekeepers, there has been rising tension in the
army and population over the country's rapid slide into bankruptcy.
Diplomats believe it is unlikely the RPF is involved in an assassination as
it was close to negotiating a share in power.
</TEXT>
<XX>
