<HEADLINE>
FT  07 APR 94 / Teamsters start haulage strike
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Picket lines went up across the US yesterday as the once powerful Teamsters'
union launched its first big strike in 15 years against 22 road haulage
companies, but little immediate effect was felt on deliveries, George Graham
reports from Washington.
Mr Ron Carey, Teamsters' president, called about 75,000 members out on
strike after talks broke down over haulage companies' plan to use more
part-time workers and to send more goods by rail. 'We have no other choice
but to strike,' Mr Carey said.
The companies targeted by the Teamsters' strike, which belong to a
negotiating consortium called Trucking Management Inc, handle about half of
all consolidated road freight in the US - single loads made up of
consignments that on their own make up less than a full truck-load. They
include haulage companies such as Consolidated Freightways, ABF Freight
Systems, and Roadway Express, which have faced increasing competition from
parcel delivery companies such as UPS.
The strike is most likely to affect deliveries of manufacturing components,
small finished goods and non-perishable groceries, but is not expected to
constrict food supplies, since most supermarket chains have their own truck
fleets.
The trucking companies ship between 5 and 15 per cent of their freight by
rail, but had proposed a new contract allowing up to 35 per cent to move by
rail. They also wanted a quarter of the work in their terminals to be done
by part-time workers, giving them more flexibility to deal with peaks in
demand.
Mr Carey's leadership has been challenged, and the union's finances, notably
its strike fund, are in poor shape.
</TEXT>
