<HEADLINE>
FT  07 APR 94 / UN forces chief to set up Bosnia peace talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Foreign Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
General Sir Michael Rose, the UN military commander in Bosnia, yesterday
agreed to a Bosnian Serb request to arrange talks with their Moslem enemies
on an overall ceasefire.
Gen Rose, speaking after talks with the Bosnian Serb leader, Mr Radovan
Karadzic, and military chief, General Ratko Mladic, said he had promised to
help arrange talks on a 'global cessation of hostilities'.
He said the Serbs had pledged to stop shelling the embattled Moslem enclave
of Gorazde, to which he cancelled a planned visit yesterday. At least 64
people have been killed and 300 wounded in a week-long upsurge of fighting
around the enclave, one of three so-called UN safe areas for Moslems in a
largely Serb-controlled region of eastern Bosnia.
The British officer played down the cancellation of his own trip to Gorazde.
'If they (the Serbs) don't want us to go there now, then we have to accept
that,' he said. However, the Serbs did allow a number of UN monitors to
enter the enclave.
Gen Rose appeared to accept the Serb contention that the recent push forward
by their forces around Gorazde was in response to Moslem advances in other
parts of Bosnia. The Serbian request for talks, and the UN's willingness to
treat the request as sincere, boosted hopes that the 'rolling ceasefire'
process in Bosnia could acquire fresh momentum.
However, diplomats said further progress would depend on consistent pressure
from Washington and Moscow, the architects of the Sarajevo ceasefire and the
federation pact between Bosnian Moslems and Croats.
There have been signs of internal disagreement in both capitals. In
Washington, the Pentagon has firmly ruled out air strikes against the Serbs
in the Gorazde area, while the US State Department has been less
categorical. The White House was understood to be working yesterday to
hammer out a common US approach to the peace effort.
In Moscow, the Duma or lower house of parliament has voted to discuss calls
for an end to Russian participation in sanctions against former Yugoslavia.
A vote against sanctions would weaken the authority of President Boris
Yeltsin's administration, although its legal impact would be unclear.
Control of all or part of the Gorazde area would bring the Serbian side
closer to its goal of linking Serbia with Serb-controlled areas of Bosnia.
There is speculation that the Serbs might be prepared to trade territory in
northern Bosnia if they could establish control over Gorazde and the other
Moslem enclaves.
</TEXT>
