<HEADLINE>
FT  07 APR 94 / International Company News: Hongs prepare for climate change
 -Groups are searching further afield for fresh gains
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE LUCAS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Turning in strong profit growth last year was, for a Hong Kong-based
conglomerate, arguably like stealing candy from a child. The colony's hongs
all hold respectable land banks, at a time when demand is far outstripping
supply, and are tapped into important infrastructure projects at various
stages of development.
However, with a strictly controlled supply of new land - just 50 hotly
fought-after hectares a year - the developers are casting their nets further
afield, buying up plots across the border in China to create commercial and
residential units. The conglomerates are doing likewise and are exploring
new lines of business in fields such as communications, industry and
aviation.
Wharf, which has an asset base of about HKDollars 100.5bn (USDollars 13bn),
is moving into cable TV and telecommunications. Hutchison is increasing its
container terminal interests and preparing for the April launch of its
revamped UK telecoms business. Swire Pacific is investing more in ports and
bottling activities in China.
With the exception of the container terminals, none of these new projects
are expected to make a large impact on the remaining financial statements
this century.
Mr Edmund Brandt, investment analyst with Jardine Fleming, does not see
Wharf's cable TV making a large contribution to profits before 2000.
In 1993, Wharf derived 75 per cent of its HKDollars 2.7bn profits from
property. Over the next three years three new development projects adding 6m
sq ft will come on line. The increased supply, twinned with rising rentals,
will sustain growth over that period.
Earlier this year, Citic Pacific, the Beijing-controlled conglomerate, paid
HKDollars 3.4bn for a 50 per cent share in Discovery Bay, a residential
complex on one of Hong Kong's outlying islands. This will see its property
earnings increase in the current financial year. Last year, the property
portfolio was valued at HKDollars 5bn.
Citic is positioning itself for the changed climate with power station
interests in China (a path followed by Hutchison) and remains on the
acquisition trail for both properties and investment/management stakes.
For Swire Pacific, where overall earnings were eroded by the fall in profits
at Cathay Pacific, the 1993 picture was property driven. About half the
profits came from this source and are expected to rise to about 60 per cent
this year. The group has a HKDollars 56.2bn portfolio of investment
properties and is in one of the strongest positions to carry on milking the
property cow.
Bucking the trend of strong property earnings last year, Jardine Matheson's
Hongkong Land, its 32 per cent owned property investment arm, reported flat
net earnings of USDollars 306.5m, compared with USDollars 305m in 1992,
partially due to losses at Trafalgar House.
Mr Ravi Nahrain, head of research at Peregrine, notes that Swire's
commercial property portfolio eclipses that of Hongkong Land's. Only four
years ago, Hongkong Land's was double the size of Swire's.
'Hongkong Land was the largest commercial property landlord on Hong Kong
island. Now it has quite clearly been replaced by Swire Properties. On a
divisional breakdown, the driving force for Swire's earnings for the past
couple of years and looking forward will certainly be Swire Properties. They
have acquired what is arguably the best property investment portfolio in
Hong Kong, and that will grow by a further 50 per cent - at least - in the
next five years,' Mr Nahrain says.
Swire is addressing the supply constraints on land in a more conservative
manner. There is no flashy bidding at auctions, the preferred route for
many. It is not calling on the Hong Kong and Chinese governments to free up
more land, like Hutchison chairman Mr Li Ka-shing. Unlike Jardine, it is not
selling out in favour of foreign fields.
Swire Properties will add almost HKDollars 4bn to its net asset value by
transforming a bowling alley and cinema, owned by the group, into an office
building, simply for the construction cost. It has teamed up with the likes
of Citic and China Motor Bus to acquire plots at prices deemed to be on the
low side.
The group has a good prospect in its Tai Koo development on Hong Kong
island. Office rentals here are about a third of those in the prime business
district of central, but the area is well served by public transport and is
closer to the airport. An increasing number of companies are relocating
staff there, including some of the colony's biggest employers such as
Jardine Pacific, Hongkong Telecom and Swire
On top of demand, there is room for rentals to move upwards. Mr Nahrain
reckons another 50 per cent is within reach over 18 months, whereas it is
unlikely that prime Exchange Square rentals will rise to the same level of
HKDollars 150 a sq ft.
Aviation, possibly the weak link after the profits fall at Cathay Pacific,
has proved more of a mixed blessing. Dragon Air, the regional airline in
which both Citic and Cathay Pacific have large stakes, is reckoned to have
grown more than 80 per cent last year, according to Peregrine. Earnings at
Hongkong Aircraft Engineering Company rose 15 per cent last year. As Cathay
turns round, so aviation contributions will swell.
The exciting stories in the years ahead will be in the fields of
infrastructure and communications. Container terminals will become more
valuable to those companies which have invested in the ports, and are
expected to become the driving force for Hutchison's earnings.
In communications, Citic will this financial year reap an additional
HKDollars 250m in earnings from its stake in Hongkong Telecom in its first
full-year holding, according to Crosby Securities.
China will continue to play an important role for the hongs, possibly to a
lesser extent at Jardine Matheson. According to Peregrine, the princely hong
that started the Hong Kong ballgame rolling has been a net seller of
HKDollars 7.4bn-worth of Hong Kong and China assets.
It may be churlishness ahead of the de-listing next year but Jardine is
generally deemed to have done the least in terms of a strategic blueprint to
take it up to the turn of the century. Jardine's star turn in 1993 was
Jardine Fleming, the Hong Kong merchant banking joint venture with Robert
Fleming, which saw net profits leap 166 per cent to USDollars 202m.
However, any stock market downturn will hit Jardine Fleming. Analysts also
fear the parent will find it tougher to do business in China following the
de-listing.
