<HEADLINE>
FT  06 APR 94 / Dutch toy workers protest in UK
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Closing a plant in the Netherlands can be a notoriously complex and
expensive process, but it does not normally involve all employees travelling
abroad to demonstrate.
Yesterday morning all 162 employees of the Hasbro toy factory in Ter Apel in
the Netherlands arrived at the doors of the Hasbro International
headquarters in Stockley Park, near London, to stage an orderly protest.
The world's biggest toy company knew the visit was planned and had earlier
turned down employee requests for a meeting with Mr Norman Walker, president
of Hasbro International.
But when the Hasbro executives saw the Dutch workers - mainly members of the
CNV general union and the FNV print union - shivering outside, their hearts
melted.
'Some of them looked as if they were suffering from hypothermia so we
invited them in for coffee and sandwiches', said Mr Peter Waterman, a
spokesman for the company.
Once inside, they also met Mr Walker who explained that he could not discuss
the proposed closure until the Ter Apel employee works council had produced
its alternative plan, with the help of consultants whom the company has to
pay for.
The Dutch employees of the nearly Dollars 3bn (Pounds 2bn) turnover toy and
games company feel aggrieved that Ter Apel has been selected for closure
despite its being, on Hasbro's own admission, a modern, efficient and
profitable plant. The trouble is, says Hasbro, that worldwide over-capacity
requires the closure of one of its three European plants and the Dutch plant
is smaller than those in Spain and Ireland and it also is not equipped to
produce both games and toys.
'As a publicly quoted company on the New York and London stock exchanges,
the company has an international responsibility to run its business in the
most cost effective and viable way possible,' said a press release from
Hasbro.
If this is the modern face of European industrial relations, it certainly
seems civilised. The Dutchmen and women chartered a Boeing 737-300 to fly
from Eelde to Luton on a public holiday but Mr Waterman said that the
company would have given them a day off to protest anyway.
The protest itself will change nothing but the 162 jobs may nonetheless be
'locked in' by Dutch employment legislation. If no agreement is reached
between the company and its employees on the alternative plan, the issue
will go to a local labour court where a judge may require Hasbro to keep the
plant open.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Hasbro Inc.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P3942 Dolls and Stuffed Toys.
    P3944 Games, Toys, and Children's Vehicles.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>PEOP  Labour.
