<HEADLINE>
FT  06 APR 94 / London Stock Exchange: Vodafone strength
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEVE THOMPSON, JOEL KIBAZO and PETER JOHN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Cellular telephones group Vodafone outpaced the market's other leading
telecoms stocks, delivering one of the best individual performances in the
FT-SE 100 after announcing a record number of new subscribers.
In March 58,500 new subscribers signed up with Vodafone, topping the
previous monthly record achieved in December 1993, and giving Vodafone a
customer base of 1.17m subscribers.
The March sales helped offset the impact of press comment highlighting the
threat to existing cellular companies by the imminent launch of Orange,
Hutchison Telecom's new mobile telephone service.
Vodafone raced up 20 to 536p after good turnover of 4.1m. BT firmed 1/2 to
393p after news that BT's Cellnet attracted 46,900 new customers last month,
taking its subscriber base through the 1m mark.
Cable and Wireless, whose One-2-One system is seen as most vulnerable to
competition from Orange, lost 3 at 452p.
News that Channel tunnel operator Eurotunnel had settled its long dispute
with construction consortium TML turned out to be a mixed blessing. Analysts
appreciated the settlement but the stock declined 10 to 505p on fears that
the company might make a bigger than anticipated rights issue. The market
was also surprised to hear that Swiss Bank Corporation has emerged as one of
the lead underwriters of the rights issue.
Market watchers were focusing on reports that Eurotunnel's anticipated
rights issue, originally intended to raise Pounds 500m before the end of
June, may now be in the region of Pounds 750m. The company said it is to
seek shareholder approval for the issue of 150m shares should the need
arise.
A sudden burst of strength in crude oil prices, amid stories that some of
the big international hedge funds have been baling out of stocks and bonds
and shifting cash into crude oil futures, helped oil shares rise.
The biggest impact was on the exploration and production sector, usually
more sensitive than integrated oil stocks to swings in oil prices.
Enterprise Oil rallied 10 to 408p. The company's stake in the Scott Field
has increased from 12.9 per cent to 13.5 per cent.
The appointment of Mr Rudolph Agnew as chairman of Lasmo from May 24 was
given a good reception. Lasmo, which fell to 118p shortly after the market
opened, rallied to end 3 up at 124p.
The financial areas of the market were the first to respond to the early
afternoon strength in UK equities. Hopes, subsequently fulfilled, of a
strong opening on Wall Street, and talk of heavy buying of banks and
insurances by funds operating big personal equity plans, drove both sectors
sharply higher.
The big rise in the dollar boosted stocks with strong links to the Far East,
such as HSBC, which moved up 16 to 755p, and Standard Chartered, 14 ahead at
1055p.
Marketmakers were caught short of stock in Lloyds Bank, which rose 18 to
577p, Barclays, up 9 at 533p, and Abbey National, 7 1/2 firmer at 473p.
Takeover speculation in the wake of last week's news that HSBC had acquired
a 6 per cent stake continued to drive Hogg Group higher. The shares settled
17 up at 182p; turnover was 836,000 shares.
General Accident was the pick of the composite insurances, the shares
surging 24 to 644p after turnover of 1.3m on talk of strong support from
Morgan Stanley, the influential US investment bank.
United Biscuits, Britain's largest biscuits and snacks manufacturer,
performed well on speculation that RJR Nabisco, of the US, is about to sell
its tobacco interests and will then be looking to make food purchases. UB
shares added 13 at 345p. The rumour was prompted by a weekend press article
which said Nabisco was poised to offload its RJ Reynolds tobacco business to
BAT Industries for some Pounds 6.5bn. BAT bounced 14 to 472p.
Tightly held Associated British Foods jumped 18 to 577p on strong
suggestions that the group was poised to sell its retail bakery business to
Greggs. The deal would represent a small disposal for AB Foods but double
Greggs' outlets. Greggs was steady at 743p.
News that Kwik Save, the food discount company, was cutting the price of
many of its top brands in its stores restrained the shares after an early
bounce. The stock rose 10 in a weak morning market and remained unchanged at
618p as rival stocks rebounded.
Engineering and aerospace group Smiths Industries fell 9 to 465 1/2 p, after
it announced a Pounds 21.6m acquisition of a US manufacturer of electrical
heating elements.
The market appreciated an Pounds 18m acquisition by property and transport
group P&amp;O. The shares put on 20 at 713p.
</TEXT>
