<HEADLINE>
FT  06 APR 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Bonds lead Dow into solid
rebound
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US stocks surged yesterday when a rally in bonds encouraged investors to
hunt for bargains among depressed blue chip and technology issues, writes
Frank McGurty in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average finished 82.06 higher at 3,675.41, while
the more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 was 9.37 ahead at 448.29. In
the secondary markets, the American SE composite gained 6.86 at 440.99,
while the Nasdaq composite forged ahead 23.54 to 750.95 for its
second-largest one-day gain ever.
Volume on the New York SE, at 366.9m shares, was heavy. Advances led
declines by 2,152 to 324 in a mirror image of the ratio in Monday's
sell-off.
The US Treasury market, which has led stocks into a steep decline over the
past fortnight, was the catalyst for yesterday's solid rebound. Equity
investors were relieved that bond prices finally appeared to have touched
bottom after a precipitous drop which intensified over the previous two
sessions.
Steady activity overseas, as European investors returned from the Easter
holiday, contributed to a calmer atmosphere. Late in the session, the yield
on the benchmark 30-year government bond had receded nearly 13 basis points
to about 7.27 per cent, easing concern over the upward spiral in long-term
rates.
With buyers again wading into the fixed-income markets, equity investors
were more willing to take a chance, even though there was no fresh economic
news to shape sentiment. The Commerce Department released its February index
of leading indicators. But the data, showing a 0.1 per cent decline, was
close to the consensus forecast of a 0.2 per cent fall.
Still, investors snapped up a wide range of stocks, with automobile issues
showing particular strength. General Motors jumped Dollars 2 3/4 to Dollars
57 3/8 after Furman Selz added the stock to its recommended list.
Caterpillar led the way as many of the cyclical stocks, hammered in recent
sessions, staged a comeback. After a delayed opening because of an order
imbalance, the stock ended Dollars 3 up at Dollars 116 1/4 . Deere gained
Dollars 2 3/4 at Dollars 86 3/8 and United Technologies climbed Dollars 3
3/8 to Dollars 65 5/8 . Cummins Engine jumped Dollars 2 5/8 to Dollars 51
3/4 after announcing that it expected first-quarter earnings to meet or
exceed fourth-quarter results.
On the Nasdaq, technology stocks made a strong recovery after seven straight
losing sessions. Among the biggest gainers, Microsoft was Dollars 3 1/4
ahead at Dollars 87 3/4 .
Canada
Toronto stocks rebounded in relatively light trading after Monday's sharp
decline. The TSE 300 composite index gained 43.2, or 1.02 per cent, at
4,273.3 and rises outpaced falls by 544 to 271. Volume was 62.5m shares
valued at CDollars 896m. Industrial products put on 2.7 per cent and
consumer products 1.8 per cent.
Brazil
Equities in Sao Paulo recovered 5.4 per cent in light trading as bargain
hunting was seen following a fall of some 11 per cent in the Bovespa index
on Monday. The index finished 730 better at 14,280. Brokers noted that most
of the activity came from domestic investors.
</TEXT>
