<HEADLINE>
FT  06 APR 94 / Commodities and Agriculture: Copper surrenders gains -
Market Report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COPPER prices surrendered early gains at the London Metal Exchange yesterday
afternoon to end only just above last Thursday's levels. But other metals
picked themselves off their lows by the close.
'It was a very mixed day - not a great deal of business, and nothing going
in any direction for long,' commented one trader. He suggested there might
have been 'a bit of an Easter hangover'.
Copper prices struggled after an inconclusive break above Dollars 1,910 a
tonne for three months delivery. By the close of the after-hours 'kerb'
session the price was threatening to fall below the Dollars 1,900 level and
test downside targets around Dollars 1,880.
ALUMINIUM prices moved in the other direction, the three months pushing
through a Dollars 1,310 target, although fairly stiff resistance was found
above that level. Late commission house selling trimmed off some of the
market's gains and final business was at Dollars 1,314, up Dollars 5 up from
Thursday.
At the London Commodity Exchange COFFEE futures managed to stage a sharp
recovery in the afternoon after a troubled start. The July position finished
Dollars 22 higher at Dollars 1,385 after begining in the minus column
following the overnight reverse in New York.
'It managed to hold this morning though, and then there was aggressive
buying from one quarter,' one dealer said, adding that that had prompted
investment funds to move in.
Compiled from Reuter
