<HEADLINE>
FT  06 APR 94 / Commodities and Agriculture: US funds push oil price above
Dollars 14 a barrel
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES, Resources Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Oil prices held on to their sharp Easter Monday gains yesterday as European
markets resumed trading after the holiday.
The benchmark Brent blend May futures contract was at Dollars 14.34 a barrel
in late trading on London's International Petroleum Exchange, 13 cents off
the day's high but a gain of Dollars 1.09 from the pre-Easter close.
Dealers said that the rise appeared to have been triggered by US investment
funds, which had been seeking new opportunities following the recent
weakening of bond and equity prices.
Strong buying in the US markets on Monday left the oil price at its highest
point for two months.
The change in sentiment came despite the recent agreement by Opec to leave
its 24.52m-barrels-a-day production ceiling unchanged for the rest of the
year. The agreement helped drive the Brent price below Dollars 13 a barrel
to a five-year low early last week.
The question now facing dealers is whether the latest gains can be
sustained. The market fundamentals have not altered and oil demand faces its
period of greatest seasonal weakness as the northern hemisphere advances
into summer.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P1311 Crude Petroleum and Natural Gas.
