<HEADLINE>
FT  06 APR 94 / Southwestern Bell abandons cable TV link-up with Cox
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Southwestern Bell, the US regional telecommunications group, yesterday
announced it was abandoning a plan to form a Dollars 4.9bn cable television
partnership with Cox Enterprises, the privately-owned media group, because
of increasing federal government regulation of the cable industry's
finances.
This is the second large link-up between a US cable company and a local
telephone group to be abandoned this year.
It reinforces the growing belief among analysts that tie-ups between the two
industries are going to proceed much more slowly than envisaged last year
when Bell Atlantic, the Philadelphia-based phone group, and
Tele-Communications Inc, the largest cable company, appeared to set a trend
by announcing plans for a Dollars 22bn merger.
That deal was widely hailed as speeding up the availability of multimedia
interactive communications services, but Bell Atlantic and TCI abandoned
their merger plans in February.
Like Southwestern Bell, they blamed the collapse on new rules for the cable
industry announced that month by the Federal Communications Commission, the
government agency which oversees the communications industries. The FCC
demanded that the cable industry cut its prices to consumers by 7 per cent.
Mr Jim Kahan, a senior executive at Southwestern Bell, said yesterday that
the company was convinced that the new regulatory environment, created by
the 1992 Cable Reregulation Act and reflected in the FCC's new rules,
'significantly hinders the ability of the partnership as initially
structured to meet its growth and financial objectives'.
Southwestern Bell provides telecommunications services in Texas and some
neighbouring states. Atlanta-based Cox is a Dollars 2.5bn turnover media
group with interests ranging from newspapers to television broadcasting
stations.
Under the deal they announced last December, Southwestern planned to invest
Dollars 1.6bn to take a 40 per cent stake in a private partnership which
would own 21 of Cox's cable systems, with about 1.6m subscribers in 16
states. Cox and Southwestern were already partners in running cable systems
in Britain and they emphasised yesterday that they would continue to
'aggressively pursue' this venture.
</TEXT>
