<HEADLINE>
FT  06 APR 94 / Eurotunnel settles TML dispute
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Eurotunnel, the company which will operate train services through the
Channel tunnel, has settled a long-running dispute with the construction
consortium, clearing the way for a rights issue of up to Pounds 750m.
Eurotunnel said yesterday that it had agreed to pay an additional Pounds
70m-Pounds 85m to Transmanche Link (TML), the Anglo-French consortium. This
brings the total it has paid TML to Pounds 1.14bn, nearly twice the Pounds
620m original contract price. The amount is, however, considerably less than
the Pounds 1.95bn the contractors had been seeking.
The ensuing Eurotunnel rights issue, planned for mid-May, may raise up to
Pounds 750m, it emerged yesterday. It was originally intended to bring in
Pounds 500m alongside a similar amount of debt.
The agreement, reached on Friday, settles the final claim outstanding
against Eurotunnel, although it still has a Pounds 1bn claim against the
British and French railways. The settlement covers the tunnel's fixed
equipment but not rolling stock deliveries. As part of the deal, TML has
agreed, with the help of Swiss Bank Corporation, to underwrite Pounds 75m of
shares.
The size of the equity issue will depend on the extent of the delay in the
opening of the tunnel; how much the banks will lend; and the exact payment
made to the contractors, which is related to Eurotunnel's share price after
the rights issue.
Sir Alastair Morton, Eurotunnel co-chairman, described the deal as 'quite a
victory' for the company's shareholders. Eurotunnel might have held out for
a lower settlement 'but when you are coming up to a rights issue, a claim is
worth avoiding'.
Mr Neville Simms, chief executive of Tarmac and leading UK negotiator on
behalf of TML, said: 'No contractor wants to get paid five years after the
traffic goes down the track. We have found a line down the middle which both
sets of shareholders should be happy with.'
Mr Simms said the impact of the deal on provisions made by the contractors
would take more than a year to come through. No extra provisions would be
needed.
An executive at one of the French consortium members said: 'It had to be a
compromise agreement, but we received most of what we asked for.'
Eurotunnel will seek shareholders' approval to issue a further 150m shares
in each of its French and British companies, in addition to the 192m already
approved for each of them. Shareholders' meetings will be held on May 9 and
17.
Sir Alastair said a full service would operate through the tunnel by
'September/Octoberish'. He estimated the cost of the delays at tens of
millions of pounds a month, but less than the Pounds 50m a month which has
been quoted, for a total over the summer of less than Pounds 100m. He
described this as 'a large but not fundamental loss of revenue'.
Lex, Page 20
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Eurotunnel.
    Transmanche Link.
</CO>
<XX>
