<HEADLINE>
FT  06 APR 94 / Dutch toy workers fly in for protest
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Closing a plant in the Netherlands can be a notoriously complex and
expensive process, but it does not normally involve all employees travelling
abroad to demonstrate.
Yesterday morning all 162 employees of the Hasbro toy factory in Ter Apel in
the Netherlands arrived at the doors of the Hasbro International
headquarters in Stockley Park, near London, to stage an orderly protest.
The world's biggest toy company knew the visit was planned and had earlier
turned down employee requests for a meeting with Mr Norman Walker, president
of Hasbro International.
But when the Hasbro executives saw the Dutch workers - mainly members of the
CNV general union and the FNV print union - shivering outside, they changed
their minds.
Mr Walker told the demonstrators he could not discuss the proposed closure
until the Ter Apel employee works council produced its alternative plan.
The employees of the nearly Dollars 3bn (Pounds 2bn) turnover company feel
aggrieved that Ter Apel has been selected for closure despite its being, on
Hasbro's own admission, a modern, efficient, and profitable plant.
The trouble, says Hasbro, is that worldwide overcapacity requires the
closure of one of its three European plants and the Dutch plant is smaller
than those in Spain and Ireland. Also, it is not equipped to produce games
and toys.
If this is the modern face of European industrial relations, it certainly
seems civilised. The employees chartered a Boeing 737-300 on a public
holiday, but a company spokesman said that Hasbro would have given them a
day off to protest anyway.
</TEXT>
