<HEADLINE>
FT  06 APR 94 / Power costs anger large users: Electricity prices in
wholesale pool reach near-record levels
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Large energy users reacted angrily yesterday as wholesale electricity prices
in England and Wales reached near-record levels.
The price rises contrasted sharply with last month, when they were at their
lowest since privatisation three years ago.
The changes have a direct impact on the more than 1,000 large industrial
companies which buy their power on prices related directly to that of the
pool.
Yesterday's level of 3.4p per kilowatt hour was the third highest daily
average since the electricity pool, the wholesale trading market, was set up
in 1990. Pool prices are determined a day in advance with generating plant
managers saying how much they are seeking to run their stations. Today's
average price is slightly lower at 3.2p than yesterday's, but still more
than twice the average daily price of 1.5p last month. The sharp change
coincided with the end of a financial year in which there was a fierce
battle for market share.
Although the present high levels are unsustainable, following a recent deal
between the industry regulator and National Power and PowerGen, the two
largest generators, they will be cited by large power users who want the
generators' ability to influence prices reduced.
National Power and PowerGen both lost market share in the last financial
year to other producers, including Nuclear Electric. But the level they
charge remains the biggest factor in determining pool prices.
Both companies say that last month's prices are well below what would be
needed to earn an adequate return on their assets or to enable them to build
new power stations.
Mr John Stoney, energy purchasing manager for Imperial Chemical Industries,
said the changes of the last few days meant that 'we have shifted from
competitive prices to manipulated prices once again.
'The levels we had in March are what you would expect to see in a
competitive market where there is overcapacity and high stocks of coal,'
said Mr Stoney. 'The rises show how much power the major generators have
over pool prices.'
The large energy users can comfort themselves with the knowledge that pool
prices will have to drop if the generators are to keep their pledge to Prof
Stephen Littlechild, electricity regulator, that they price their power in
such a way that average annual prices do not exceed 2.4p per kwh.
Mr Peter Rost, chairman of the Major Energy Users' Association, said price
rises this month were very disruptive to his members with pool-related
contracts. They highlighted why Prof Littlechild was justified in limiting
pool prices during the next two years in his deal with the generators.
</TEXT>
