<HEADLINE>
FT  06 APR 94 / Lettuce imports threaten growers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARGREAVES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Britain's Pounds 160m market in glasshouse production of lettuces and
tomatoes is under threat because of the European single market, say growers.
Southern European countries such as Spain have been increasingly turning
their attention to high-priced northern markets, making it difficult for
northern producers reliant on energy-consuming greenhouses to compete.
Spanish shipments of iceberg lettuce to Britain are expected to rise by
10,000 tonnes this year to 79,000 tonnes. This compares with only 1,600
tonnes in 1985.
Wholesale prices have halved during the past month alone, causing severe
financial difficulties for traditional British glasshouse producers.
'We've dumped 20,000 boxes of lettuce at the top of the nursery and just
left them to rot,' said Mr Norman Lee, who runs Southgate Growers at
Chichester, West Sussex.
Mr Lee specialises in supplying during the winter when demand for salads is
low, but prices are usually high. This market is now being filled by a flood
of low-priced imports, and his receipts have dropped by 25 per cent.
Changing tastes have also led consumers to abandon the British round lettuce
in favour of more exotic imports.
Round lettuces have held their market share in previous years because they
have been considerably cheaper than imports, in spite of high energy costs.
As Spanish production has expanded, that price differential has been eroded
during the past year.
Mr Graham Ward, who runs Snaith Salad Growers in Goole, North Humberside,
believes Spanish lettuces are being sold below cost to UK supermarkets. 'The
Spanish prices are totally unrealistic,' he said.
Mr Ward says the break-even price for a box of 12 lettuces, including
transport from Spain to the UK and packing costs, would be about Pounds 2.80
to Pounds 3. But boxes of iceberg are being sold at Pounds 1.50. The drop in
price has slashed his turnover from a typical Pounds 2.5m a month to Pounds
1m in March.
Mr Colin Pickthall, Labour MP for Lancashire West, challenged the government
last week to look into the dumping of Spanish lettuce in the UK market.
Mr Michael Jack, the junior agriculture minister, replied that if growers
could supply evidence of unfair state aid to Spanish producers, he would
investigate.
Growers say it is difficult to find any decisive evidence of subsidy. But
they are infuriated that the vegetable sector should suffer from unalloyed
competition when the rest of European agriculture is supported by the common
agricultural policy.
Mr Derek Crossley, a lettuce grower near Selby, North Yorkshire, says he is
struggling to survive because he can only sell three-quarters of what he
produces.
He said: 'Over the past two years I've invested Pounds 53,000 into the
business which we'd put away to retire on, but now we've run out and I think
I'm going to go under.'
</TEXT>
