<HEADLINE>
FT  06 APR 94 / Exporters upbeat about prospects
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
British exporters are more confident about their prospects than at any time
over the past two years, says a DHL Gallup survey. But many are worried that
UK manufacturers are pricing themselves out of world markets.
Almost seven out of 10 manufacturers surveyed have good or excellent
expectations for export orders over the next 12 months and 56 per cent
believe prospects are good for the next three months.
The outlook for British exports has improved since sterling left the
exchange rate mechanism in September 1992. However, 31 per cent of
manufacturers fear that companies are using the pound's competitiveness to
raise prices and, as a consequence, are losing orders. 'We must use our
competitive edge to strive for increased market share,' said Mr Ian
Campbell, director-general of the Institute of Export.
Most companies expect an increase in sales in European Union markets. But
the US and Canada are seen as the most promising growth markets. The Pacific
Rim countries are seen as posing the greatest competitive threat.
The survey of 501 manufacturing exporters was conducted between March 10 and
March 17.
</TEXT>
