<HEADLINE>
FT  06 APR 94 / 'Superbike' designer signs contract
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The designer of the carbon fibre and titanium 'superbike' on which Briton
Chris Boardman (above) won a pursuit cycling gold medal at the 1992
Barcelona Olympic games has signed a contract to work for Giant, the
Taiwanese cycle producer, John Griffiths writes.
Mr Michael Burrows said he had become disillusioned with British industry
after failing to see his innovative ideas for cycles put into production.
Although the 'superbike' was designed by Mr Burrows, its patents are owned
by Lotus Engineering, which says the launch of a Pounds 3,000 road-going
version of the machine is imminent. Nearly two years have elapsed since
Lotus, sold recently by General Motors to Bugatti, announced it was looking
for a partner to put the cycle into production.
Lotus has designed the roadgoing superbike's components but it is to be
assembled by Casket, the cycles and clothing group which has bought the
LotuSport brand name.
Mr Burrows claims to have made his decision to join Giant only after being
ignored by British cycle makers including Raleigh, the UK's biggest
producer, which makes 600,000 cycles a year. Raleigh has denied receiving
any formal approaches from Mr Burrows.
Giant is one of the world's largest cycle manufacturers, making about 1.6m a
year, almost entirely for export. It is thus one of the UK industry's
fiercest competitors.
After the success of his Olympic design, the self-taught Mr Burrows designed
another cycle, on which Scot Graeme Obree cycled a world record 51.597
kilometres in an hour last July.
'It's sad that it's not an English company,' said Mr Burrows, who will
undertake concept engineering for Giant from his base in Norfolk. 'But their
engineers want to learn and it could be the perfect combination. If I can
give Giant the technological edge there'll be no stopping them.'
</TEXT>
