<HEADLINE>
FT  06 APR 94 / 2,000 advisers apply to PIA
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Personal Investment Authority, the new watchdog to protect private
investors, had by yesterday received just over 2,000 applications from
companies and individuals wanting to be regulated by it, Alison Smith
writes.
When the PIA published its prospectus in February, it estimated there were
about 6,000 potential members who now come under the existing
self-regulating organisations, Lautro and Fimbra. The PIA will open in July
and has warned life companies and independent financial advisers that if
they missed yesterday's deadline it cannot guarantee that applications will
be processed by then.
The decision by Prudential, the UK's largest life insurer, to reject the PIA
and be regulated directly by the Securities and Investments Board has
intensified caution within the financial services industry over the PIA's
future, leading many potential members to hang back before applying.
Bradford &amp; Bingley, the seventh-largest building society, yesterday
announced it had applied to join the PIA. Mr Geoffrey Lister, its chief
executive, is on the PIA board.
</TEXT>
