<HEADLINE>
FT  06 APR 94 / CBI recommends debt ombudsman
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD GOURLAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Confederation of British Industry yesterday called on the government to
tackle the problem of late payment of trade debts, but said legislation for
a statutory right to interest would not work.
The government should instead consider establishing a 'commercial debt
ombudsman' with powers to investigate complaints against the government and
businesses and to publicise its findings.
Government organisations should be required to pay promptly and a system
should be devised to ensure that suppliers to the government pay their own
suppliers promptly.
The CBI made the submissions to the Department of Trade and Industry in
response to a consultative document produced after the last Budget called
for a solution for late payment.
The CBI said quoted companies should be required to specify their payment
policies in annual reports and whether they support the CBI code of practice
on prompt payment. The government should consider a British Standard on
prompt payment.
Mr John Parsons, chairman of the CBI's Smaller Firms Council, said: 'If a
law could be devised to solve the problem of late payment, the CBI would be
the first to support it.
'But our smaller-firm members do not think legislation for a statutory right
to interest would work. Dominant customers who have paid late in the past
will have few qualms about insisting on longer payment terms.'
</TEXT>
