<HEADLINE>
FT  06 APR 94 / World Trade News: Information technology on EU-US agenda
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
European business leaders and Commission officials meet their US
counterparts today in an attempt to relieve tensions over market access and
standardisation in the European and US information technology sectors,
writes Gillian Tett in Brussels.
The meeting, in New York, marks the Commission's first public attempt to
consult US officials about its ambitious plans to develop an information
network infrastructure in Europe, unveiled by Mr Jaques Delors, Commission
president, last year.
A working group of European industrialists, led by Mr Carlo de Benedetti and
Viscount Etienne Davignon, are due to present proposals on financing and
operating these highways to Brussels later this month.
However, Commission officials admit progress is limited in their attempts to
agree the type of common information technology standards necessary to
develop any transatlantic or global information networks.
Coming amid US complaints that European policy on IT telecommunications
patents has been overly restrictive, standardisation is expected to be a key
issue at today's meeting, Commission officials said.
