<HEADLINE>
FT  06 APR 94 / Balladur presses ahead on jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Edouard Balladur, the French prime minister, went on television yesterday
to stress that his government will press ahead with its five-year employment
law despite being forced to retract plans to allow apprentices to be paid
less than the minimum wage. Under the new measure, companies will receive a
subsidy of FFr1,000 (Pounds 114.54) for each employee under 18 to whom they
give a first job. Mr Michel Giraud, the labour minister, said decrees on tax
credits for apprenticeships and job training and measures to promote
part-time working would be promulgated soon.
