<HEADLINE>
FT  06 APR 94 / Rutskoi vows to topple Yeltsin
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN LLOYD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Alexander Rutskoi, the former Russian vice-president and recently
released coup plotter, said yesterday he would fight to remove President
Boris Yeltsin by legal means. His voice joins a growing opposition to Mr
Yeltsin's efforts to achieve consensus. In an interview in the pro-Communist
Pravda, Mr Rutskoi said: 'We must stop playing with consensus or agreements
and get down to work - to change the authorities by legal means.' Mr Rutskoi
is positioning himself to run for president in the next elections.
Mr Vladimir Zhirinovsky, the Liberal Democrat leader who is also a declared
candidate for the presidency, has said he sees Mr Rutskoi as his greatest
challenge. Mr Yeltsin has been trying to get an agreement with the
parliament on a 'Memorandum on Civil Accord'. But Mr Gennady Zyuganov,
leader of the Communist party, last week dismissed the accord, saying he
could not accept its moratorium on changes to the constitution.
