<HEADLINE>
FT  06 APR 94 / Bristol &amp; West head was paid almost Pounds 1/2 m to quit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Bristol &amp; West, the UK's tenth largest building society, has paid out almost
Pounds 500,000 in compensation for loss of office to its former chief
executive, a near-record payment for a building society.
Mr Tony FitzSimons, who left abruptly last September, received Pounds
415,000 in compensation for loss of salary, and a further Pounds 69,000 in
enhanced pension contributions.
The society's annual report and accounts also reveal that Bristol &amp; West has
a three-year contract with a company run by Mr FitzSimons for consultancy
services at a rate of Pounds 50,000 a year.
The society's 1992 results saw a drop in pre-tax profits to Pounds 39.1m
from Pounds 67.4m, as it had to triple provisions for possible bad debts on
mortgage lending to Pounds 74.1m, having been badly hit by the fall in house
prices in the south of England.
Mr John Wriglesworth, societies analyst at stockbroker UBS, said that
Bristol &amp; West had been 'dogged by over-expansionist lending in the heady
days of 1989 and 1990, and over-zealous spending both on acquisitions -
notably Hamptons, the estate agency - and on technology in the branch
network'.
This had resulted, he said, in a loss of confidence in a traditionally
strong society, although under Mr John Burke, formerly deputy chief
executive who succeeded Mr FitzSimons, the society's performance was already
improving.
From his appointment as chief executive in spring 1989 to his resignation
last autumn, Mr FitzSimons was a controversial figure. In December 1992, for
example, he said that Bristol &amp; West would become the first society to price
new mortgages according to the borrower's age and family status.
The payments to Mr FitzSimons - who served less than five years - are
rivalled only by the Pounds 641,000 paid to Mr Scott Durward, who resigned
from Alliance &amp; Leicester, the UK's fourth largest society, in 1991 after
ten years as chief executive.
A more typical payment to an executive director leaving a large society
would be about Pounds 250,000.
Bristol &amp; West said yesterday that the board thought it was 'in the
society's interest' to make it possible for Mr FitzSimons to depart without
being required to serve out his two-year notice period, and the compensation
payments reflected this.
Bristol &amp; West said there had been other occasions, though not at chief
executive level, when a senior executive who had left the society had
undertaken consultancy work because of specialised knowledge and experience.
Going through a tendering process before awarding a contract to Mr
FitzSimons' company 'would not have been relevant', it said.
The society's 1993 results, announced last month, showed both the scale of
its poor results and the beginnings of recovery. Its pre-tax profits rose to
Pounds 41.3m, helped by a fall in bad debt provisions to Pounds 63.3m, while
its 1992 results were restated - in the light of new accounting standards -
as just Pounds 14m.
</TEXT>
