<HEADLINE>
FT  05 APR 94 / Steinhardt makes first move in UK
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Steinhardt Partners, one of the world's top three hedge fund managers, has
launched its first raid on a quoted UK company, as a first step towards
making a series of substantial investments in debt-stricken European
businesses.
Over the past two months, Steinhardt, which has equity under management of
around Dollars 5bn (Pounds 3.4bn) but borrows many billions more for
investment, has quietly acquired a 30 per cent stake in the convertible
preference shares of Ransomes, the lossmaking manufacturer of grass cutting
equipment.
Even though this gives Steinhardt a fully diluted stake of just under 15 per
cent in the company - well above the 3 per cent level that normally obliges
public disclosure of a holding - the shares are currently non-voting, so
there has probably not been a legal obligation to disclose.
However, the convertible preference shares become voting instruments when
dividends are six months in arrears.
Ransomes made pre-tax losses of Pounds 8.9m in 1993 and it postponed the
payment of the preference dividend due last October 31. As a result, holders
of the preference shares should receive votes at the end of the month,
giving Steinhardt a potentially influential stake in the company.
A financier with a close knowledge of Steinhardt's European plans said that
although a full bid for Ransomes could not be ruled out, the fund's normal
preference was to take a strategic holding and then persuade a company to
adopt a reorganisation plan.
Steinhardt, which paid around Pounds 10m for the Ransomes stake, is
understood to believe the company has a solid operating business but will be
unable to thrive until the burden of paying interest on Pounds 75m of bank
debt and dividends on Pounds 56.6m of convertible preference shares is
reduced by a significant injection of equity.
The financier said that Steinhardt was also examining a series of other
investments in over-borrowed European companies.
Like Soros Fund Management and Tiger, its two main hedge fund rivals,
Steinhardt typically invests in very liquid instruments - particularly
currency and interest rate derivatives - with the aim of making enormous
profits from movements in foreign exchange or bond markets.
However, like Soros, it also takes substantial stakes in companies. In the
US, it has invested hundreds of million dollars in businesses with excessive
debts in order to facilitate financial reconstructions. For example,
Steinhardt has been battling with a consortium linked to Continental
Airlines over proposals to recapitalise America West Airlines, the US
carrier in Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection.
Mr Michael Steinhardt, founder of the fund, is consistently ranked as one of
Wall Street's biggest earners, alongside Mr George Soros, earning hundreds
of million dollar a year.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Steinhardt Partners.
    Ransomes.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
    GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P3524 Lawn and Garden Equipment.
    P6799 Investors, NEC.
</IN>
