<HEADLINE>
FT  05 APR 94 / NUT conference paves way for strike action
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The National Union of Teachers, the UK's largest teachers' union, yesterday
opened the way for strikes against a string of government education
policies.
Mr Doug McAvoy, the NUT's general secretary, attempted to play down
prospects of the votes at the union's annual conference leading to
widespread classroom disruption. He was responding to strong criticism of
the conference decisions from ministers and rival trade unions.
The NUT on Sunday isolated itself from the other unions by pressing ahead
with plans for an indefinite boycott of the government's national curriculum
tests.
During the conference, which started in Scarborough on Saturday and ends
today, leftwing delegates committed the union to strike plans over rising
class sizes, cuts in grants to schools with a high number of ethnic minority
children and new contracts for teachers in sixth-form colleges. The NUT
conference is traditionally militant, but this year's decisions mark a
significant shift in power towards the left.
Members have also reserved the right to strike over pupil tests, which will
be boycotted indefinitely, and to refuse to co-operate with 'anti-trade
union legislation'.
However, a motion calling for strike plans in support of a flat-rate Pounds
3,000 pay increase was defeated in a rare success for the moderate
executive.
The leaders of the rival teachers' unions have distanced themselves from the
NUT. Mr Nigel de Gruchy, general-secretary of the National Association of
Schoolmasters Union of Women Teachers, said: 'What's going on at the NUT
conference doesn't represent the majority view of the profession.'
Mr McAvoy claimed there would be no widespread disruption. Any school
wishing to take industrial action would need to obtain a two-thirds majority
of its members in a ballot and then seek approval, both from the union's
local division and the action committee of the national executive which is
dominated by moderates. Many delegates had voted in line with factions at
the conference, but he predicted they would not persuade teachers to take
prolonged strike action, which would be needed to force concessions from the
government.
Mr John Patten, education secretary, said he was 'really very saddened'.
'I think parents will be frankly bewildered that just when standards are
beginning to improve in this country we suddenly seem to be back in the
1960s, with threats of one-day strikes right in the middle of the A-level
period,' he added.
Mr Tony Lloyd, shadow education minister, said Mr Patten should resolve the
crisis by calling in all the teachers' unions to hammer things out.
'These tests still have very little value for the pupils involved. They are
all about saving John Patten's face,' Mr Lloyd told BBC Radio 4's The World
at One.
Mr Don Foster, Liberal Democrat education spokesman, said: 'It would have
been very much more sensible for the NUT to co-operate with the five other
teacher unions.'
