<HEADLINE>
FT  05 APR 94 / Recovery 'still buoyant': Managers report a record increase
in manufacturing activity
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The recovery is still buoyant, say two reports published yesterday - the day
before the full impact of the government's tax rises starts to hit
consumers.
There was a record increase in manufacturing activity last month, the
purchasing managers' index found, while a survey of investment intentions
indicates that almost two out of three UK companies intend to buy a
substantial asset over the next three months.
The two reports will sustain hopes that the corporate sector can maintain
the strength of the recovery by increased investment, even if consumer
spending flags in the face of the tax increases.
The purchasing managers' index rose from 55.5 per cent in February to 56.6
per cent in March, its highest recorded level. The index, compiled by the
Chartered Institute of Purchasing and Supply, is based on a weighted survey
of variables such as new orders and suppliers' delivery times. Any level
above 50 per cent represents an increase over the previous month.
Mr Peter Thomson, director-general of the institute, said: 'Output and new
orders have soared in the face of strong demand from the domestic market.
There is every indication that the acceleration in activity will continue.'
The companies surveyed also reported an increase in employment.
The one discouraging note reported by the institute is that upward pressure
on prices from suppliers' annual price reviews continued last month.
The Lombard Business Investment Survey, conducted by NOP, finds 61 per cent
of businesses likely to buy an important asset over the next three months,
the same level as in December. About 68 per cent of the companies surveyed
say that the tax increases will make no difference to their investment
plans.
However, there is a slight downturn in the proportion of businesses planning
to acquire a substantial asset over the next 12 months. This has fallen to
77 per cent from 83 per cent in December.
Mr Paul Gee, marketing director at Lombard Business Finance, said: 'Our
overall assessment of the survey results is that, although investment
intentions remain high, general business confidence is levelling off.'
About 63 per cent of companies surveyed expect their turnover to be higher
in real terms over the next three months than it was a year ago, while 12
per cent expect turnover to be lower. This positive balance of 51 per cent
compares with 53 per cent in December.
The Lombard survey shows a continuing pick-up in confidence in construction,
but the transport and distribution sector seems to have been most affected
by the prospect of tax increases. The sector's investment intentions and its
expectations of increased turnover have declined sharply since December.
The assets most likely to be purchased over the next three months are
manufacturing equipment, construction equipment and information technology.
There has been a decline in the proportion of companies intending to
purchase telecommunications equipment, cars and commercial vehicles.
The survey is based on telephone interviews with 451 finance directors.
